Conclusion

The Hospital Patient Management System successfully demonstrates the application of core data structures, 
namely arrays and queues, in solving a practical real-world problem.
The system provides a clean, interactive console interface that allows hospital staff to manage patient records effectively through four key operations:
adding, viewing, searching, and deleting patients.

The use of an array for patient storage enables straightforward indexed access and linear traversal,
while the STL queue ensures patients are maintained in a fair first-come-first-served waiting order. 
The modular function design keeps the code organized, readable, and easy to extend. Input validation and boundary checks ensure the program handles edge cases gracefully without crashing.

Through testing, all operations were verified to work correctly,
including error handling for cases such as an empty patient list, a full array, and patient IDs that do not exist in the system.
The system met all its defined objectives and performs efficiently within the constraints of the data size.

In conclusion, this project reinforced the importance of choosing appropriate data structures for a given problem.
Arrays are ideal for direct indexed access and compact storage, while queues naturally model real-world waiting scenarios.
The project provides a strong foundation that can be extended into a more comprehensive hospital information system in future work.




